    {
      "id": "el_36",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 62,
      "y": 1703,
      "width": 262,
      "height": 18,
      "text": "Laws of Exponents",
      "fontSize": 14,
      "fontFamily": 1,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "baseline": 14,
      "strokeColor": "#2f9e44",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "seed": 3600,
      "version": 1,
      "versionNonce": 36,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "groupIds": [
        "f_2_0"
      ],
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Laws of Exponents",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null
    },
    {
      "id": "el_37",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 62,
      "y": 1725,
      "width": 406,
      "height": 172,
      "text": "a^m x a^n = a^(m+n)    Product rule\na^m / a^n = a^(m-n)    Division rule\n(a^m)^n   = a^(m x n)  Power of power\n(ab)^n    = a^n x b^n   Power of product\na^0 = 1    a^(-n) = 1/a^n    a^(1/n) = nth root of a\n\nWHY: a^m × a^n = (a×...m)(a×...n) = a repeated m+n\ntimes\n  Division removes n copies → m-n remain\n\nEx: 2^3 × 2^4 = 8×16 = 128 = 2^7 (3+4=7) ✓",
      "fontSize": 13,
      "fontFamily": 3,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "baseline": 13,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "seed": 3700,
      "version": 1,
      "versionNonce": 37,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "groupIds": [
        "f_2_0"
      ],
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "a^m x a^n = a^(m+n)    Product rule\na^m / a^n = a^(m-n)    Division rule\n(a^m)^n   = a^(m x n)  Power of power\n(ab)^n    = a^n x b^n   Power of product\na^0 = 1    a^(-n) = 1/a^n    a^(1/n) = nth root of a\n\nWHY: a^m × a^n = (a×...m)(a×...n) = a repeated m+n\ntimes\n  Division removes n copies → m-n remain\n\nEx: 2^3 × 2^4 = 8×16 = 128 = 2^7 (3+4=7) ✓",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null
    },
